items.Definition: Posthole in bedrock in NE part of room 35
items.Interpretation: If this is in fact a posthole cut, it may have been meant for shelves or some other wooden structure in association with the use of the two cuts for pithos bases; from its position, it may not have functioned while the eastern cut was being used, but it is difficult to say what its chronological relationship with the other cuts may have been

items.Description: A thin lense of fine ashy gray loose soil that is approximately 1M (NW-SE) X 70 cm (NE-SW) and 5-10 cm in depth. Most of it was much closer to 5 than 10 cm. The layer was irregularly shaped and difficult to define.
items.Definition: Fine ashy gray patch in NW area 3 in courtyard
items.Interpretation: Fill associated with context 0877, possibly related to metalworking activities.
items.Observations: Allyson has this context extent on plan. Because this context and 0877 were so fine they were easily mixed, there was real difficulty detemining which context covered which. Finally a cut profile clearly showed 876 over 0877. However, there may have been several alternating mixed layers of these gray and black super fine soils.

items.Description: Layer of relatively compact soil (includes two large stones) in the northern part of cut 901 extending under wall 264.  The soil was more compact under the large stones but the material was of consistent color, texture and inclusions. At its extent, this layer included no more than 20 square centimeters of soil. The soil lacked a great deal of debris, though the majority of the material was "special."
items.Definition: Compact brown soil in cut 0901, room 38
items.Interpretation: This is a fill layer, compacted in some areas from the weight of the stones above (or, perhaps, at one point in time from usage - though this area of material is just too small to be able to tell) and looser in the corners. The material in this area tends to be late Roman in date, though the finds here seem to be later.
items.Observations: A bit of incertainty about the relative compactness of the soil in some places, but not all, in this layer. I have attributed this to the stones and our stepping on the area while getting in and out of cut 728 but, this could be misguided. So, I treated both slightly compact and more compact soil at the same level as the same material, and same context.

items.Description: Soft greyish soil with inclusions of pebbles , small stones, many animal bones, large quantities of pottery, distinct (at least in excavation) from material at same level on other side of removed wall
items.Definition: Layer of soft grayish soil in East and South part of room 37
items.Interpretation: Fill was made to level the surface in the last phase of use
items.Observations: may have been equal to 596; DVD thinks different, on the basis of the finds; cxt sheet reads "some chance that distinction between 575 and 596 is artificial -- no clear limit observed"

items.Description: Includes stones of different sizes; ceramic fragments (with different dating - mostly Byz[antine]); frags of glass goods; iron slag frags (iron nails, other metal goods). The quantity of the soil in the upper horizons is less than the lower, colour from dark gray to gray.
items.Definition: Collapse in room 30
items.Interpretation: The collapse of the walls of the room
items.Observations: Tile not counted. Presence of ceramics (not a lot) and later metal goods. Glazed ceramics present in the SW corner; [in the same corner,] remains of a wooden object with vertical direction of lines in it (bad preservation).

items.Description: Dark gray soil with large tile pieces. Medium compaction, small charcoal inclusions, small ceramic inclusions. Located under layer identified as SR 348; possibly bottom layer of the collapse.
items.Definition: lower layer of tile collapse and ash in room 29
items.Interpretation: July 13, 2005: joins in the ceramics found in this layer, SR 348, and SR 355 suggest that all three layers were formed during the same destruction moment, and the perception of different levels during excavation may have been false (these levels, however, even if arbitrary, allowed the creation of a more complex digital plan of the tile collapse in this room)
items.Observations: July 13, 2005: see interpretation above: ceramic analysis after excavation season identified joins between pithos sherds and other pottery across this layer, SR 348, and SR 355

items.Description: Layer characterized by an high concentration of tiles, of which the most part laid  flat. Mixed with gray soil and  few stones; pottery, few inclusions of charcoal. In one case a piece of around 3 cm (sample 356). Next to the walls the tiles were mixed with seagrass (sample 368). It is extended all over the room abutting structures around. The surface is higher along the edges of the room. It is recorded a depression (?) next to 536 and 559.
items.Definition: Layer of tiles collapse in room 38
items.Interpretation: Layer of the first collapse of the roof that lay on the floor (surface of trampling) 610, indicated bythe layer of articulated vassels (580).

items.Description: longitudinal object, parallel sided; circular cross-section 0,5 cm dia. Solid. Copper/copper alloy. Generally corroded/encrusted throughout. One end appears to taper to a beak shaped point.
Fragment of copper/copper alloy strip-original thickness 0.05 cm. Heavily corroded and encrusted
Very heavily encrusted and corroded. "T" shape in profile. Encrustations mask evidence of original form.

Copper/copper alloy (green corrosion product); long element with convergent sides (from 0,5 cm width to 0,2 cm); at wider end, waisted and extending to semi- circular element 0,3 cm by 0,7 cm wide of same thickness and in same plane originally but which appears to have been bent back upon itself; encrustations all surfaces.

Longitudinal, heavily corroded/encrusted. Both ends appear to develop to points. One face appears relatively flat,the other has domincal appearance in cross section. Some evidence at one end that original may have had a triangular cross section.

Diamond shaped piece of flat iron with a 0.3 cm hole through the centre. Round shaft, broken at end, leads off from one corner (metal visible in break), and a small cylindrical tip leads off the opposite.

Irregular shaped, roughly oblong, heavily encrusted and corroded; profile and cross- section uncertain; at one end flat 0,5 cm wide, becoming bulbous centrallly and possibly suffering twist damage, the other end revealing roughly flat cross- section (0,4 cm- 0,7 cm) bu rotated from the plane of the other end by ca 45 degrees; lug-like element 0,9 cm wide (0,3 cm- 0,4 cm thick) projects 0,5 cm from one edge (apparently originally in the same plane but suffering bend damage by ca. 60 degrees) 1,2 cm from one end.
Fragment of planoconvex bone tool, handle, or inlay plaque.
Punta ripiegata; sez. quadrata. Diam. Testa 2cm

Copper/copper alloy wire, less then 0,1 cm dia. All surfaces corroded. Some encrustation at 2 junctions. 5 linked elements, hook loop linked to 4 looped elements. Hook: 1,9 cm long, dia of hook 0,9 cm look 0,35 cm dia, twisted through 90 degrees. 2nd element: 0,4 cm dia. Loop linked to 2nd look by 0.6 cm shaft; twisted through 90 degrees. 3rd element: as above; length of shaft ca. 7,5 cm. 4th element: as 2nd element. 5th element: 0.4 cm dia loop, 2.6 cm (remainder) of shaft. (By analogy with Sarachane (Istanbul) example, element 5 would have terminated in a hook and carried a further 2 hangers - type "C")
roughly square in plan, ellipsoidal in end cross-section; mass of heavily corroded/encrusted, fissured; no discernable form or feature.
